# Sankey4Salesforce — Project Rules

You are an expert Salesforce platform developer and architect. You write clean, standard, SLDS-compliant Lightning Web Components with layered Apex backends. You follow Salesforce's latest documented best practices.

## Salesforce Platform Constraints

- **No CDN loading.** All third-party JS must be uploaded as a Static Resource (CSP blocks external scripts).
- **Sandboxed runtime.** Lightning Web Security provides no real `window` global and no cross-component DOM access. Code must operate only inside the component root.
- **LWC owns the DOM.** D3 may only render into elements marked `lwc:dom="manual"`. Never manipulate DOM that LWC manages.
- **No Bootstrap or external CSS.** Use SLDS utilities for layout and component `.css` for chart-specific styles only.

## Project Architecture

```
force-app/main/default/
├── lwc/
│   ├── dsSankeyBuilder/      # Parent orchestrator (exposed)
│   ├── dsEmptyState/         # First-time onboarding
│   ├── dsObjectPicker/       # Permission-aware object autocomplete with type-ahead search
│   ├── dsMetricSelector/     # Count vs Amount metric picker
│   ├── dsPathSelector/       # Ordered path field selector with scored top-5 auto-selection
│   ├── dsFilterBuilder/      # SOQL filter builder UI
│   ├── dsSankeyChart/        # D3 Sankey rendering (lwc:dom="manual")
│   ├── dsTracePanel/         # Record Trace + Flow Trace controls
│   ├── dsInsightsPanel/      # KPIs and top paths sidebar
│   ├── dsSavedConfigs/       # Save/load config via Apex
│   ├── dsSaveConfigModal/    # LightningModal for save dialog
│   └── dsUtils/              # Shared pure utility functions
├── classes/
│   ├── SankeyController.cls          # @AuraEnabled entry points
│   ├── SankeyService.cls             # Path aggregation + KPI computation
│   ├── SankeyQueryBuilder.cls        # Dynamic SOQL builder
│   ├── SankeyConfigRepository.cls    # CRUD for DS_Sankey_Config__c
│   ├── SankeyControllerTest.cls
│   └── SankeyServiceTest.cls
├── objects/
│   └── DS_Sankey_Config__c/          # Saved configuration storage
└── staticresources/
    └── d3.zip                        # D3 v7 + d3-sankey (minified)
```

## Component Communication Pattern

Parent orchestrator (`dsSankeyBuilder`) owns all state. Children receive data via `@api` and communicate up via `CustomEvent`. Never store shared state in child components.

```
dsSankeyBuilder (state owner)
 ├── @api down → dsObjectPicker, dsMetricSelector, dsPathSelector, ...
 ├── @api down → dsSankeyChart (nodes, links, records, mode, trace state)
 └── CustomEvent up ← all children (objectselect, loaddata, nodeclick, ...)
```

## LWC Template Standards

### Use modern conditional directives — NEVER use deprecated `if:true` / `if:false`

```html
<!-- CORRECT -->
<template lwc:if={hasData}>...</template>
<template lwc:elseif={isLoading}>...</template>
<template lwc:else>...</template>

<!-- NEVER — these are deprecated -->
<template if:true={hasData}>...</template>
<template if:false={hasData}>...</template>
```

When `lwc:else` cannot be a direct sibling of `lwc:if`, create a negated getter (e.g., `get noData() { return !this.hasData; }`) and use `lwc:if={noData}`.

### Use `lwc:dom="manual"` only on elements D3 controls

```html
<svg class="sankey" lwc:dom="manual"></svg>
```

## LWC JavaScript Standards

### DOM access — always scoped

```javascript
// NEVER
document.querySelector('svg');

// ALWAYS
this.template.querySelector('svg');
```

### D3 loading — guard with a flag, load once

```javascript
import { loadScript } from 'lightning/platformResourceLoader';
import D3_RESOURCE from '@salesforce/resourceUrl/d3';

renderedCallback() {
    if (this._d3Loaded) return;
    this._d3Loaded = true;
    loadScript(this, D3_RESOURCE + '/d3.min.js')
        .then(() => this._initChart());
}
```

### Prefer @api setters over renderedCallback for change detection

Do not JSON.stringify data in `renderedCallback` for diffing. Use `@api` setters with dirty flags:

```javascript
_nodes = [];
_dataChanged = false;

@api get nodes() { return this._nodes; }
set nodes(val) {
    this._nodes = val || [];
    this._dataChanged = true;
}

renderedCallback() {
    if (this._dataChanged) {
        this._dataChanged = false;
        this._rebuildGraph();
    }
}
```

### Never mutate reactive properties in loops

```javascript
// BAD — triggers rerender per iteration
this.nodes.forEach(n => { this.processedData.push(transform(n)); });

// GOOD — assign once
const result = this.nodes.map(n => transform(n));
this.processedData = result;
```

### Use ShowToastEvent for user feedback

```javascript
import { ShowToastEvent } from 'lightning/platformShowToastEvent';

this.dispatchEvent(new ShowToastEvent({
    title: 'Success',
    message: 'Data loaded.',
    variant: 'success'
}));
```

### Use LightningModal for dialogs — never raw SLDS modal markup

Create a separate component extending `LightningModal`:

```javascript
import LightningModal from 'lightning/modal';

export default class MyModal extends LightningModal {
    handleSave() { this.close(result); }
}
```

Open it imperatively from the parent:

```javascript
const result = await MyModal.open({ size: 'small', label: 'Title' });
```

### Sort field option lists by type priority

When building field option lists from `getObjectInfo`, sort by data type priority (picklist first, then short text, then numbers, then everything else), with alphabetical sorting within each group:

```javascript
const TYPE_PRIORITY = {
    Picklist: 0,
    String: 1, Phone: 1, Email: 1, Url: 1,
    Currency: 2, Double: 2, Int: 2, Long: 2, Percent: 2
};

Object.keys(fields)
    .sort((a, b) => {
        const pa = TYPE_PRIORITY[fields[a].dataType] ?? 3;
        const pb = TYPE_PRIORITY[fields[b].dataType] ?? 3;
        return pa !== pb ? pa - pb : fields[a].label.localeCompare(fields[b].label);
    })
    .map(key => ({ label: fields[key].label + ' (' + key + ')', value: key }));
```

`dsPathSelector` and `dsFilterBuilder` both use this pattern. `dsPathSelector` also auto-selects the top 5 fields on fresh object selection using a three-component scored ranking (100 pts max): data-type score (Picklist 40, Reference 25, Text 10), population score (recentPct * 0.3, max 30), and cardinality score (3–20 unique values = 30 pts ideal, 2 or 21–40 = 15 pts, else 0). Falls back to first 5 picklists alphabetically when stats are unavailable. Skipped when loading saved configs.

### Use NavigationMixin for record navigation

```javascript
import { NavigationMixin } from 'lightning/navigation';

this[NavigationMixin.Navigate]({
    type: 'standard__recordPage',
    attributes: { recordId, actionName: 'view' }
});
```

## CSS / Styling Standards

### Use SLDS design token CSS custom properties — never hardcode Salesforce colors

```css
/* CORRECT — adapts to dark mode, themes, and branding */
color: var(--slds-g-color-neutral-base-50, var(--lwc-colorTextWeak, #706e6b));
background: var(--slds-g-color-neutral-base-95, var(--lwc-colorBackground, #f4f6f9));
border: 1px solid var(--slds-g-color-border-base-1, var(--lwc-colorBorder, #e5e5e5));

/* NEVER — breaks in dark mode and custom themes */
color: #706e6b;
background: #f4f6f9;
```

Always provide a fallback chain: `var(--slds-g-*, var(--lwc-*, <hex-fallback>))`.

### Use SLDS utilities for layout, component CSS for chart styles only

```html
<div class="slds-grid slds-gutters slds-wrap">
    <div class="slds-col slds-size_1-of-2">...</div>
</div>
```

### Use `slds-box` for visual containers — avoid nesting `lightning-card` inside `lightning-card`

## Apex Standards

### Security — always enforce

- All classes: `public with sharing class ...`
- All queries: `WITH SECURITY_ENFORCED`
- All user input: `String.escapeSingleQuotes()`

### Governor limit protection

- Enforce `LIMIT` on all queries (default: 10,000)
- Use Maps instead of nested loops for aggregation
- Never issue SOQL inside a loop

### DRY — extract shared logic

When two methods share identical logic (e.g., WHERE clause building), extract to a `private static` helper.

### Sorting — use Comparable, not manual loops

```apex
private class PathEntry implements Comparable {
    public Decimal sortVal;
    public Integer compareTo(Object other) {
        PathEntry that = (PathEntry) other;
        if (that.sortVal > this.sortVal) return 1;
        if (that.sortVal < this.sortVal) return -1;
        return 0;
    }
}

entries.sort(); // native platform sort
```

## D3 Rendering Rules

### Incremental updates over full SVG rebuilds

On mode/trace/highlight changes, restyle existing elements (opacity, stroke, class). Only rebuild the SVG when the underlying dataset changes.

### Container sizing with ResizeObserver

LWC runs in App pages, Record pages, and Console tabs. Use `ResizeObserver` on the chart container to recompute layout dynamically.

### Accessibility on SVG output

```javascript
svg.attr('role', 'img').attr('aria-label', 'Sankey flow diagram');
ng.each(function(d) {
    d3.select(this).attr('aria-label', d.label);
});
```

## Deployment

### Meta XML — expose only top-level components

```xml
<!-- dsSankeyBuilder (exposed) -->
<isExposed>true</isExposed>
<targets>
    <target>lightning__AppPage</target>
    <target>lightning__RecordPage</target>
    <target>lightning__HomePage</target>
</targets>

<!-- All child components -->
<isExposed>false</isExposed>
```

### Deploy command

```bash
sf config set target-org <alias>
sf project deploy start --source-dir force-app --wait 10
```

### D3 static resource rebuild

```bash
npm run build:d3   # runs scripts/build-d3.js
```

## Code Quality

- Keep JSDoc on class and public method level only — avoid per-line narration comments
- Do not add comments that just restate what the code does
- Test files may reference story/acceptance criteria for traceability
- Prefer `const` over `let`; never use `var`
- Use template literals or string concatenation consistently (this project uses concatenation)
